\subsection{The pattern |squig y x|}

What does the strange pattern |y squiggt x| do?  As you can see from rule \rulename{msquig}, it
allows you access to the \emph{input} of the match as well as the \emph{output}.  So in
$$
|f( (squig y x) : abs ) := dots|
$$
in a call |f(-4)|, |x| gets bound to |4|, but |y| gets bound to the original input, |(-4)|.

This is useful for arrays.  Suppose |a| is an array.  Consider the Source Verse terms
|x:a| and |x := :a|.
The two are equivalent; remember rule \rulename{pcolont}.
Both use |a| as a type, but arrays are functions, so that's fine. \simon{Its not an idempotent function though!
  Here we are usefully using a non-idempotent function as a ``type''.}\lennart{I think it's worth pointing out that
  types are idempotent functions, but the the |t| in |:t| does not have to be a type.  It can be any function.}
Then |(x := :a)| desugars (via \rulename{dexpr} and \rulename{mtype}) to |x := def i (a^[i])|.
Then our execution semantics for arrays rewrites thus:
$$
|a^[i]| \longrightarrow |(i=0; v_1) `choice` dots `choice` (i=n; v_n)|
$$
where the elements of |a| are |v_0, dots, v_n|.  So the net effect is that |x:a| binds |x| successively
to the elements of |a|; it is an implicit for-loop.
We can use |for| to build a new array; thus |for(x:a){x+1}| returns an array the same size as |a| but
with each element increased by 1.

Now consider |(squig i x):a|.  That binds |i| and |x| successively to the \emph{index/value} pairs of |a|.
How does that happen?  Consider
$$
\begin{array}{ll}
  |De ((squig i x) := :a)| \\
  \rightarrow \{\rulename{dexpr}\} &
    |def j (Me j ((squig i x) := :a))| \\
  \rightarrow \{\rulename{msquig}\} &
    |def j (x := (Me j (:a)); i := j| \\
  \rightarrow \{\rulename{mtype}\} &
    |def j (x := a^[j]; i := j| \\
  \rightarrow \{\text{bind |x| and |i| and rewrite}\} &
  |def (i x) (dots (x = a^[i]) dots)|
\end{array}
$$
Clever!  Incidentally, from \rulename{msquig} you can see that the form |x := t| is redundant
in the syntax of Small Source Verse.
We could just have |(squig y x) := t| with a fresh |y|.  But the for |x := t| is so
ubiquitously useful that we include it in our syntax.

\subsection{Open functions}

\Cref{fig:open} gives extra rules for open functions.

Rule \rulename{u-olam} comes directly from rule \rulename{c-mutatate-ll} in Fig 10-13 of the extendded version of the extended version of ``The essence of ML type inference'' (Pottier and Remy) \url{http://cristal.inria.fr/attapl/}.

Here is an example. Assume the function definitions are open.
$$
\begin{array}{ll}
  \multicolumn{2}{l}{|f^(x:int) := x+1; f^(x:float) := x*0.2; f^[2.4]|} \\[1mm]
  \movesto & \mbox{\{desugar\}} \\
  & |defhdr f| \begin{array}[t]{l}
    |f = def z_1 (olam z_1 (lam i (apply1N int i)) (lam x (x+1)));| \\
    |f = def z_2 (olam z_2 (lam i (apply1N float i)) (lam x (x*0.2)));| \\
    |f^[2.4]|
    \end{array} \\[10mm]
  \movesto & \mbox{\{substitute for f, and discard f\}} \\
  & |defhdr (z_1 z_2)| \begin{array}[t]{l}
    |(olam z_1 (lam i (apply1N int i)) (lam x (x+1)))
      == (olam z_2 (lam i (apply1N float i)) (lam x (x*0.2)));| \\
    |(olam z_1 (lam i (apply1N int i)) (lam x (x+1)))^[2.4]|
    \end{array}\\[6mm]
  \movesto & \mbox{\{\rulename{u-olam} and \rulename{app-olam}\}} \\
  & |defhdr (z_1 z_2 z_3)| \begin{array}[t]{l}
    |z_1 == olam z_3 (lam (i) (check fails (apply1N int i); apply1N float i)) (x*0.2);| \\
    |z_2 == olam z_3 (lam (i) (check fails (apply1N float i); apply1N int i)) (x+1);| \\
    |if (x:=int^[2.4]) then (x+1) else apply1N z_1 2.4|
    \end{array}\\[10mm]
  \movesto & \mbox{\{Simplify |if|, discard |z_2|\}} \\
  & |defhdr (z_1 z_3)| \begin{array}[t]{l}
    |z_1 == olam z_3 (lam (i) (check fails (apply1N int i); apply1N float i)) (x*0.2);| \\
    |apply1N z_1 2.4|
    \end{array}\\[7mm]
  \movesto & \mbox{\{substitute for |z_1|, then discard |z_1|, and \rulename{app-olam}\}} \\
  & |def (z_3) (if (x := (check fails (apply1N int 2.4); apply1N float 2.4)) then (x*0.2) else apply1N z_3 2.4| \\[2mm]
 \movesto & \mbox{\{Simplify |if|\}} \\
  & |def (z_3) (2.4 * 0.2)| \\[2mm]
 \movesto & \mbox{\{arithmetic and GC\}} \\
  & |0.48| \\
\end{array}
$$
\subsection{Loose ends}

\begin{itemize}
\item Is \rulename{meq} right. E.g. |functionP ( x:= (:nat = :even) ) t| should
  check that both |nat^[i]| and |even^[i]| succeed \emph{and} that they give the same result.
\item \simon{Is \rulename{moftype} right?}
\item Koen points out that \rulename{mfor} is awkwardly different to \rulename{mif}.
\item |(Me i t)| is very syntatic. It treats |:t| and |id (:t)| differently for example.
  Ditto$$
  \begin{array}{l}
    |f (:abs,:abs) := ...| \\
    |f ( for(1 `choice` 2){:abs} ) := ...|
    \end{array}
  $$
\end{itemize}

